<font color="#FF0000">DIFFERENT WORLDS AND VALUES</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct  8 23:50:47 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Class Lass,<br><br>
It is without a doubt everyone's privilege and right to express opinion and beliefs.  I am sure that most vets grieve for those who did not return.  Others suffer the imprint that can not be erased.<br><br>
Protestors exercised their privileges and in doing so became the comforter of others besides our countrymen.  We can't have it both ways.  This breech of faith or act of betrayal is certainly the choice of those that stayed behind  Equally so it is the right of the veteran to not forgive such violations.  From both sides it is asking a modification of value, honor, and integrity.<br><br>
Most would say a middle ground is possible, but forgiveness may be beyond my grasp.  I can not forgive and find it difficult to look the other way.  A matter of choice.<br>

